Brand Nubian One For All: 32 years ago today this dropped. It got off to a sleepy start, my promo team were lames and the bands defiant stance freaked some cornballs at the label out (I loved it!) only to become a milestone in the Golden Era of Hip Hop. Given 5 mics by The Source when that meant something, and praised by their peers coast to coast Brand Nubian was one of the most important groups I ever worked with. I learnt a lot about life, how to move correctly and was taught to give an artist space, to allow them to express them selves sans censorship, to amplify their messaging whenever possible and how to be a champion of such. I thank my brothers @lordjamar @sadat_dotty_ @therealgrandpuba and @alamoworld for allowing me to be a part of this. Rest Easy Terry Hall🙏🏼. 
The Specials were one of my entry drugs into the world of ska, punk and reggae at the tender age of 14.  I listened to the first 2 albums as much as any records made by any band ever. One of those groups that just got it. Everyone in my age group with any sense of taste loved them. Terry Hall and his comrades had style, a wicked sense of humor, an important message, and most of all fantastic songs. They were bigger than the genre of Ska itself. He was a large part of that equation. 

I saw them in my youth, first at The Hotel Diplomat at age 14, and every time they toured in any city I was in after. He was and will ways be the definition of British cool to me. 
His working class lyrics, smooth voice and detached sense of youthful anger stands the test of time. One of my personal hero’s. His music will live on forever. A Message To Rudy indeed🕊🕊🕊

Jeff Beck is one of the reasons I became obsessed with guitar players as a adolescent. When I first heard Becks Bolero I was floored. I studied his early work in the Yardbirds, his amazing Jeff Beck band work with and without Rod The Mod. Truth,Beck-Ola and The Jeff Beck Band LPs are all great. His playing particularly on the Jeff Beck Band record is phenomenal. He had a sensitivity and subtlety in his playing that was rare. His turn towards Jazz Fusion was also top notch. Blow By Blow, Wired and There and Back are excellent testements to his growth as a player. I mean how many times have those Come Dancing drums been used for Boom Bap joints? 
His later turn (Return? Slight Return?) as a blues player was interesting as well. 
He always had an identifiable sound, I preferred him far more than Clapton, other than Hendrix and SRV I rate him my favorite guitarist. 
From tone to pure shredding ability he was a bad MFer. I urge you to listen to a tune he cut almost 20 years ago called Brush With The Blues its mind blowing, as is his cover of Mingus’ Goodbye Pork Pie Hat. Most  don’t know he actually played the drums on Stevie Wonders Superstition wild right? It was originally a Jeff Beck song but Berry Gordy insisted Stevie keep it. In turn Stevie gave him the gorgeous Cause We Ended As Lovers from Blow By Blow which remains some of Becks best playing ever on record. Saw him live a bunch of times, he was a bad ass to the highest power. Rest Easy King,  I will always love your playing it was original, soulful, lyrical and had a sensitivity that was unique. 
🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼Play On Mr. Beck  #RIPJB 🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼

I encountered these people at the vigil in Monterey Park last night. These people are my people. Say what you will, but enough is enough, we have had more mass shootings than days of the year so far, we need to address the situation once and for all. I believe a ban on all assault rifle sales in America is a start. Much tougher penalty’s on anyone caught carrying any form of illegal fire arm. Mandatory 10 year sentences for anyone caught with an illegal assault rifle. In depth background checks on any and all gun licenses and gun purchases, both handguns and rifles of any type. Honestly, the whole we need our assault rifles argument stinks of Lil D**k energy. A ban on assault rifles is not a infringement on our personal rites IMO. I don’t have all the answers, I do know where my moral compass resides, we have to stop the killing now. The ease with which one can legally buy an assault rifle increases the likelihood of more mass shootings, no ifs, ands or buts. The need for affordable and available mental health care is needed yesterday, in conjunction with a re-examination of the 2nd amendment. How long till we have another mass shooting done with a legally purchased assault rifle… again? I refuse to debate this issue with anyone anymore, my line is drawn in the sand. The vigil in Monterey Park last night was a heavy scene to say the least. My thoughts are with those that were victims of this tragedy, their family’s and friends and all victims of mass shootings familys in America🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼

The Captain: Willis Reed, the reason I love the NY Knicks and Basketball. 
Let me explain: in 1973 Willis injured his leg yet played that legendary game seven against the Lakers scoring 2 baskets in the open minutes  inspiring The Knick to their last championship ring. I watched that game on my family’s 19 inch b/w with my father,  who was visiting from California.
A few days later, my dad convinced me to write a letter to Willis Reed, wishing him a speedy recovery. Mysteriously,  I received Willis Reed’s autograph in the mail a few weeks later. I never knew it was real or not. I am still not sure if my dad faked it, or if it was the genuine article, if some Knicks publicist at MSG signed it and sent me it or if the infamous autographed photo of Willis was official tissue. 
Doesn’t matter really,  the end result was it made me a lifelong Willis Reed and New York Knicks fan. My love for Basketball has never dwindled. It never will, it was the common ground me and my father met on, for the remainder our entire lives. Basketball, The Knicks and Willis Reed are at the center of it all.  Thank you for your service Captain, we love you, Willis Reed. Rest Easy Big Man🙏🏼

Seymour Stein, you truly were one of a kind. An icon, a real record man. I knew of you long before I got to know you. You are one of the reasons people like me do A and R. You opened the door for The Ramones, Talking Heads, Richard Hell, Ice T, and Madonna, to name a few of the wonderful artists you helped bring to the world. I mean, Seymour applied the term New Wave to music, creating a whole genre to try to get The Talking Heads and The Ramones on the radio. How HUGE is that?

You were always gracious, funny, and a pleasure to kibitz with, your James Brown/ Rick Derringer at the Apollo story is one of the greatest music biz stories I have ever heard. 
Having lunch with you was always beyond entertaining. You never held back, and I loved hearing every second of it!
I was so lucky to have an office down the hall from you and be able to pop in to see you, pick your brain, and listen to your wonderful stories, which were plentiful; that jukebox collection wasn’t too bad either!

You understood music and artistry in buckets; so sad you have left this plane of existence, but so happy I got to give you your flowers before you departed. You were the last of a dying breed. Missing her so much today. We are so similar its uncanny, the good and the bad. My mother always meant well, and like me, sometimes she just didn’t know what to do. She always tried her best, despite the hand she was dealt. My mother raised two kids by herself, she slept on the pull-out sofa bed most of my childhood and got up and went to work every day, despite fighting her internal demons, see she had to put food on the table so she did.
Like a lot of single mothers, she was selfless, strong yet vulnerable, and full of empathy. She never turned anyone away from our table despite us not having much. Because of my mother, more than anyone who ever walked this earth I turned out OK. My sense of integrity and ethics comes directly from her, as does my want for social justice. I post about my dad a lot, but it was my mom who did the heavy lifting. She taught me about art, music, film, how and what to read and to believe in myself. My mother was my biggest champion. My evolved tastes are directly translatable to her, particularly my love of Soul music, she loved herself some Aretha, Etta James and Otis Redding. I thank her for my life as I know it. Happy Mothers day to all the Mothers in this world, we love you, we salute you, without our mothers, we as sons are nothing🙏🏼 #HappyMothersDay #SingleMothers #SonsandMothers #OGratitude

Herb Sundays 86: Dante Ross (@danteross). The legendary A&R and producer shares an extended New York-centric Sunday afternoon playlist.

(Apple, Spotify, Tidal, Amazon via @substackinc). Art by @michaelcina. 

Ross is considered one of the best to wear an a&r hat for finding underground talent that has had a wider appeal without sacrificing political or artistic goals including artists such as De La Soul, Queen Latifah, Brand Nubian, Del the Funky Homosapien, Pete Rock & CL Smooth, KMD, and Ol' Dirty Bastard.

Dante has a new autobiography out, Son Of The City (via @rarebirdli) which given his gift for storytelling is incredible. 

He has been quick to acknowledge his privilege as a white male, which gave him access to corporate circles to serve his taste. There is a list longer than this email of unsung heroes of indie culture including the women and minorities who helped this culture grow. This group forms sort of “second ring” of talent behind the talent development and mythmaking of Hip-Hop, Punk, and Skate that led to the rise of alternative culture in the mainstream.

The playlist is the sound of NYC in the past, but you’ll still catch whiffs of it still coming out of cars. Nothing is better than hearing slow disco drums emanating through the streets of NYC through the gloaming. 

“Before hip-hop consumed my life (and my crew's), we listened to what we then called ‘club music’ alongside early hip-hop and post-punk/new wave. As a kid, I had a gig skating a half pipe in a nightclub called Area in Tribeca for a summer.

After work, my friend the fabulous Ms. Lysa Cooper, and a crew of super hip, beautiful girls and guys would go to the legendary Paradise Garage and dance till daylight, then go to Rockaway Beach and nap on the beach. Psychedelics were often in the mix.

The sound, the music, and possibly the drugs made it the greatest dance party I have ever been to. It was a black, pansexual forerunner to a rave...

Anyways these tunes are a little reflection of those times and what I like to listen to at the house when I'm just relaxing. Very little hip-hop gets played in the pad, on a Sunday, it makes me feel like I'm working.”

Thank you for being the most important musical movement and subculture I have ever participated in. For me, it all started with Rappers Delight in 7th grade. I loved early Hip Hop; it was party music, a new form of Disco, if you will. It was funky and exciting. 
I loved artists like The Treacherous 3, Kurtis Blow, Fearless 4, Funky 4 plus one more, Grand Master Flash and the Furious 5, Spoonie G, and Jimmy Spicer. 
In 83 RUN-DMC and Whodini showed me it was a lifestyle, and I signed on for it hook, line, and sinker, and here I am, still involved and inspired. 
RUN-DMC was as hard as concrete, and Whodini was as smooth as Corinthian leather. For me, they were like Peanut Butter and Jelly; I stayed bumping those two. Add LL and The Beasties to that mix, and I never looked back. Thank you, Hip Hop, for letting me contribute, in a small way, to the big picture. I consider it, one of the greatest honors in my entire life. Let's see where the next 50 take it🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼

Yesterday marked 25 years since this dropped. Hard to believe it. Wild ride making this one, Eric aka Everlast had a near fatal heart attack and almost died after recording the last song on the record Tired. John Gamble RIP saved his life. While Eric was recovering Gamble and I went back to NYC and mixed the record with our boy Jamey Staub, gotta say we nailed it. When It dropped , it started off slooow, but eventually it caught a wave and by December 98 the first single What Its Like was a hit record, going on the become the number 1 alternative song in the country, propelling the LP into the top 10. Eric recovered fully and went on to tour the world, and the record went Triple Platinum. Changed my entire career, and lead me to working with Santana and winning a Grammy the following year. What a ride, if you were around you would understand how crazy this experience was. If I had one wish it would be for John to be able to celebrate this with us miss Gamble a ton. Anyways read my book if you wanna know more about what went down.

I lived on 2nd ave for 17 years and drank a lot of coffee at Mud when I was getting sober over a decade ago.
We intend to evoke the spirits of the late Dave “Daisy”Parsons, the owner of the Rat Cage, who provided a safe space for us as teenagers, John Berry RIP my teenage best friend and original Beastie, plus our old friend Cookie O Puss as well as the Bad Brains who we hung out with there all the time! 
I actually worked at The Rat Cage part time when Dave started selling skateboards in 83, ( I was good a gripping boards, he wasn’t) in fact it’s where I met Joey Ramone. Dave would transition before he passed to become Daisy Parsons later in life, but before that happened, the site of Daisy skating around in a dress and some eye make up was freaking amazing🙏🏼
We loved Dave, we loved Daisy and we loved hanging out in a pre gentrified East Village/ LES. I’ll be selling and signing books, if you already copped one, bring it I’ll sign it. This is going to be fun👊🏼

Deeply saddened when I heard my friend DJ Mark the 45 King had passed this morning. Mark was a humble, super-talented, funny, and unique cat. I met him in the spring of 88 at the Latin Quarters. How he knew me, I will never know, but I knew of him, at least his music, that is, Red Alert, had been playing the promos, and his production on Latee’s This Cuts Got Flavor was ringing bells. We went up to the lounge, and he played me a slew of beats ( he had his ever-present Walkman with the studio headphones w/him) I was blown away. 
Mark and @fab5freddy called me up a few days later and played me Latifah's Wrath of My Madness over the phone. It sounded so good on my shitty little speakerphone, it was unreal. Mark and several members of the Flavor Unit would come to a meeting at Tommy Boy later that week. This is where I first met Dana Owens aka Queen Latifah. Meeting her that day would change my career and, hence, my life. 
Wait, it gets better: 
We signed her( Monica Lynch and I ) and instead of getting paid a producer fee, Mark had us arrange for his payment to be an Akai S900 sampler, which I picked up for him at Sam Ash and delivered via the Jersey Transit bus to him in East Orange aka E.O. We quickly went to his basement studio (which was amazing, he had a train turnstile and more cool memorabilia than I had ever seen anywhere before). He promptly set up the S900 and got to work. Watching Mark I learned a lot about records, being comfortable with yourself, and producing. Watching him layer and chop drum sounds changed how I made beats. Mark was a genius in the studio; his 45 DJ sets were yet another testament to his talents. He made classics for Latifah, Jay Z (Hard Knock Life) and Eminem (Stan) and my favorite Chill Rob G banger Court Is Now In Session amongst others. He gifted me a bunch of records way back when, including the Boris Gardner Melting Pot 45 and the classic The Cult- The Mail Must Go Through. Gonna play those today and remember his wonderful quirky spirit. Those days with him and Latifah remain some of the best of my entire life. Rest easy, my old friend. You were loved by all who knew you!

As a kid I wanted to be a sportswriter. In middle school I wrote an essay about Baseball and my beloved Yankees. It was entered by my English teacher Mr. Failkoff into a city wide contest, and I got 2nd place. My mother worked with a woman named Elaine Roach, her husband was a famous sports writer named James Roach, he covered Horse Racing for the NY Times. My mother showed Elaine and James my story and told them I wanted to be a sportswriter when I grew up. James took an interest in me and my dream and introduced me to, at the time the greatest living Baseball writer the legendary Red Smith, who also wrote for the NY Times. 
Red and James took a liking to me, and encouraged my dream. I was all of 12 years old, when Red took me to see my beloved Yankees at The Stadium, where we sat in the press box. After the game Red actually walked me into the clubhouse. I was speechless, its all still a blur tbh. Red passed away a few years later, I never got to thank him as an adult.
The service was at Friends Seminary Church, the Quaker church where, I would attend 12 Step meetings 35 years later.  I always thought about Red when I went to those meetings. Should have told my Red  Smith story in my book. I literally forgot, that one of my first dreams was to become a sports writer. I think I might have been able to do it, shit Mark Kriegel pulled it off, right? 

Anyways, thanks for  the encouragement Uncle Red Smith, I had no idea how much of a giant you were back then. Man, some of the grownups like James Roach, his wife Eliane and the legendary Red Smith were such amazing and gracious people. I haven’t thought about them in decades, I miss them, and my parents #OGratitude 🙏🏼
